Descriptive Analysis

Anonymous

13 8 2020

This doc gives some exploratory insight into the DataSet

A total of n=174 completed the questionnaire at least to the point of the bonus questions.

Demographics:

Almost all participants stated, that they did experience a videogame as art:

Freq % Valid
Yes 168 96.551724
No 6 3.448276

Age and Gender were distributed as follows:

The Experience of Videogames as Art.

Of the 174 participants, 168 indicated they experienced games as art.

We asked the participants who indicated that they had an experience where they considered games as art to describe this experience and to explain why they consider this experience to be art. We further offered them to answer a set of bonus questions. Of the 168 participants, 158 agreed to do so (Though 18 participants did not follow through). These bonus questions asked, what the participants think the meaning of the experience was, how this specific experience changed their opinion on the game, how it effected their personal life, how the experience changed their opinion of the medium, and if they thought their experience was intended by the developers.

Changed Perspective on Game: (out of 150) Changed Perspective on Self: (out of 150) Changed Perspective on Medium: (out of 150) Experience was the Developers Intention (out of 150)
120 92 61 131

It should be noted, that many participants who indicated that the experience did not change their opinion on the medium stated that they already saw games as a form of art (e.g., ID 8, 12, 67, 87, 116). This may indicate, that at least among video game players, the discussion that games are art is not really held anymore.

We further asked participants to state up to five of their favorite games. We compared these to the game they described as an artful experience.

Of the 168 participants indicating an artful videogame experience, 89 (52.98%) counted the game as one of their favourites. It has to be noted, that this observation might, in part be due to the availability of said title, as the recollection task was done before the participants named up to five of their favourite games.

Another confounding factor might be that many participants recounted a rather recent experience:

It has to be noted, that while Skyrim is by far the game mentioned most often as a favourite, only 2 people (ID456, 666) mentioned it as their artful experience.

For 72.02% of participants, the experience happened during their first exposure to the game.

When asked where in the game the experience happened, many participants indicated, that the experience happened during the general gameplay, not at any specific moment. People who indicated Other, often times pointed out, that the whole game was deemed as the described experience (e.g., ID 11, 13, 20, 22, 27). Further, it could be that when mentioning their favourite game, not all people specified that they meant The Last of Us Part 2, leading to a higher mention of it as a favourite game while Part 2 was mentioned more often as an artful experience. (Further, two people indicated both The Last of Us 1 and 2 as their favourite games)

Expertise and AESTHEMOS

Exploring Expertise

Expertise was measured via several measures: - For how long have they been playing (in Years) - how many hours do they play per week - Self reported Experience (0-100) - Self reported broadness of taste (0-100) - A selection of Genres people prefer

TimeInYears_mean TimeInYears_SD TimePerWeek_mean TimePerWeek_SD SelfReportedExperience_mean SelfReportedExperience_SD SelfReportedBroadnessOfTaste_mean SelfReportedBroadnessOfTaste EnjoyedGenres_mean EnjoyedGenres_SD
18.10345 7.997159 14.7069 13.01001 78.71598 22.12039 63.78363 28.39646 6.574713 2.966605

Expertise was measured directly via two continuous self report measures:

  • Experience
  • Broadness of Taste

These two measures had a medium correlation (r = 0.4192103). Ths indicates, that a higher experience might come with a broadened taste.

Additionally participants indicated the time since they started playing

The measures had a medium correlation (r = 0.3105851)

As expected, the self report of broadness of taste correlates highly with the enjoyed genres (r = 0.5749135).

Further, participants indicated if they worked in the gaming industry or worked as Artists:

Of the 174 participants, 25 worked on or with video games and 49 worked on or with art. 16 participants described themselves as working or having worked in both fields. Interestingly, one participants (ID620) works in both fields while stating to not have had an artistic experience. However, this might not be due to an absence of an artistic experience but due to the participants rejection of the [] Art, as its commonly understood and applied in general discourse [].

While people working with videogames barely differentiate themselves from the other participants, they report a slightly broader taste. However, given the vast different in sample size, this should be taken with a grain of salt.

The Absence of Videogames as Art.

Few people indicated, that they never had any experience with video games that they would classify as art 6 (3.45%). Of these 4 (66.67%) indicated they had experience with other forms of art. As written before, ID620 indicated, that they did not believe in the term art and therefore did not agree with any of the questions.

Besides ID620 only one other person noted, that videogames cannot be experienced as art as, while the parts my be art, the game itself is only a vessel and therefore not itself art.

Of the 6 people, 4 people (50%) indicated they experienced art with other mediums. Two of which where with visual art, one with music and one noted It held a critical position and oriented itself as a model for engaging with the visual landscape in a novel/critical way (ID319), which might indicated a form of natural beauty or maybe theoretical model.
